IMPORTANT INFORMATION FOR INCOMING KINDERGARTEN FAMILIES:

Kindergarten Orientation will be held the week of September 14th for all kindergarten students plus one parent. Schools will send home invitation letters with specific dates, times, locations and activities planned for Kindergarten Orientation days.

Kindergarten students will begin their first virtual class via Zoom on Monday, September 21st at 9:00 AM. This will give parents time to attend the Kindergarten Orientation, become familiar with the login process, and pick-up instructional materials.

The Junior Honor Guard represents all WOHS Juniors who have earned all A's and B's during their time at WOHS from Freshman year up until the 3rd marking period of their Junior year. This year, 66 students earned this recognition; which is the largest number to date!!

Typically the Junior Honor Guard participates in graduation every year, lining up as the graduates enter the arena and remain on the floor as honorary guests. Due to the maximum capacities set by the Governor for the live graduation ceremonies, the Junior Honor Guard will unfortunately not be present at the July 8th in-person graduation ceremonies.

CLASS OF 2020!! For many of you, you're completely done!! For others, there's still some oustanding obligations that need to be completed in order to receive your diplomas.

A new online payment system has been created for seniors to pay these obligations. This adheres to health & safety measures for no one to exchange money by hand.

All seniors and parents/guardians please check and ensure that all outstanding obligations have been paid. All obligations must be paid before a senior can receive his/her diploma. You can submit payment for your obligation at https://payments.efundsforschools.com/v3/districts/56333

If you have any questions, please send an email to: scowins@westorangeschools.org

post_text:
Updated Statement from Board of Education 6/3/2020

Acknowledging the need for more direct and thoughtful communication on a very important topic, the West Orange Board of Education recognizes that our statement published yesterday fell short for our community, and we apologize.

We join all families in sadness over the wrongful death of George Floyd. At no point was our intention to minimize the pain that so many of our West Orange families and staff are experiencing or to fail to recognize and reaffirm that Black Lives Matter.

We are all committed to doing our part to work with the administration and community to identify and create sustainable action, and to amplify the work this Board has done and will continue to do for the equity of our black/brown students and their families. Watch for a further statement detailing this past, current, and future work.

We are listening. We are ready to work. We are West Orange.

Ken Alper, President
Terry Trigg-Scales, Vice President
Cheryl Merklinger, Board Member
Jennifer Tunnicliffe, Board Member
Gary Rothstein, Board Member

ALUMNI SPOTLIGHT: West Orange High School Class of 2008 alumnus Zachary Ehrlich volunteered to work for the COVID-19 emergency team at the New Jersey Department of Health. Ehrlich currently works at the NJDOH as an inspector in the Public Health and Food Protection Program but has been conducting epidemiology work during the pandemic.

He graduated from Montclair State University and then New York Medical College with a Master of Public Health in environmental health science.

This month, Ehrlich was inducted into the Delta Omega Honorary Society in Public Health. Earlier this year, he received the Vincent R. Zurawski Award for meritorious contributions to the field by the New Jersey Environmental Health Association.

Ehrlich‚Äôs father is a doctor and his mom is a retired nurse, whom inspired him to go into public health. WOHS teacher Hope Stewart was one of his biggest inspirations to go into the environmental sub-field.

Keep making us proud!! #WOstrong
text:
ALUMNI SPOTLIGHT: West Orange High School Class of 2008 alumnus Zachary Ehrlich volunteered to work for the COVID-19 emergency team at the New Jersey Department of Health. Ehrlich currently works at the NJDOH as an inspector in the Public Health and Food Protection Program but has been conducting epidemiology work during the pandemic.

He graduated from Montclair State University and then New York Medical College with a Master of Public Health in environmental health science.

This month, Ehrlich was inducted into the Delta Omega Honorary Society in Public Health. Earlier this year, he received the Vincent R. Zurawski Award for meritorious contributions to the field by the New Jersey Environmental Health Association.

Ehrlich‚Äôs father is a doctor and his mom is a retired nurse, whom inspired him to go into public health. WOHS teacher Hope Stewart was one of his biggest inspirations to go into the environmental sub-field.

Keep making us proud!! #WOstrong

post_text: Updated information from the Holy Trinity-West Orange Food Pantry
shared_text:
Holy Trinity-West Orange Food Pantry
April 14 at 2:06 AM ¬∑

Hi West Orange Community!

Here is our latest update.

We provided food for several hundred people this past week, including seniors, sick, families, and individuals.

The Food Pantry will be open to give out food Tues. April 14 and Thurs. April 16 from 10am - 12 pm.

You do not have to be a member to receive food. Come to the red door on the Franklin Ave. side of Holy Trinity Episcopal Church, located at 315 Main St. All are welcome.

We are continuing to work with the WO Department of Senior Services to shop and deliver to seniors and homebound. Seniors and homebound, contact Laura Van Dyke at 973-325-4105 to coordinate. All others, call or text Cynthia Cumming at the Food Pantry at 201-41-9217 or email Heidlercumming@aol.com.

School district families in need are also welcome.

This week, we can use:

Spaghetti sauce and pasta
Cereal
Tea, regular and green
Dry beans
Eggs
Bread
Butter

He touched the hearts of many and will be greatly missed. Please join us in offering sincerest condolences to the Suriano family. #WOPride

Holy Trinity-West Orange Food Pantry
April 6 at 1:06 AM ¬∑

Thank you West Orange Community for your continued support of our food pantry over the past several weeks. We have been able to provide hundreds of bags of food and supplies to senior citizens and community families.

We have been shopping for specific items for several of the families and seniors as well. The pantry will open for special distribution hours on Tues. April 7 and Thurs. April 9 from 10 am to 12 pm.

Delivery is available for seniors and homebound. We ask that families make every effort to come to the pantry to pick up food, but we will do our best to accommodate hardships.

Financial donations are welcome, and this week, we can use the following:

Spaghetti sauce and pasta
Cereal
Tea, regular and green
Dry beans
Eggs
Bread

These items can be dropped off during pantry hours or dropped to 58 Valley Way, the home of Cynthia Cumming, Administrator. Senior citizens and homebound, continue to reach out to Laura Van Dyke at the Department of Senior Services at 973-325-4105. School families, out of work individual and others, email heidlercumming@aol.com or call 201-341-9217.

ùêçùêÄùêìùêàùêéùêçùêÄùêã ùêáùêéùêçùêéùêë ùêíùêéùêÇùêàùêÑùêìùêò ùêîùêèùêÉùêÄùêìùêÑ:

Due to the unprecedented nature of the Coronavirus Pandemic, the National Honor Society application process and induction ceremony will be moved to the Fall of the 2020 - 2021 school year. As we do not have an official return date to school, this decision is in the best interest of rising senior students, allowing them time to complete the application and have the induction ceremony they deserve in the beginning of the 2020 - 2021 school year. Moving the application due date to the fall will also allow rising seniors to focus on E-Learning at this time and not stress about completing the application. Additionally, this provides the advisors and the NHS committee team a chance to properly and equitably review all applications to ensure that every student has a fair chance of becoming a National Honor Society member. Lastly, we want to assure students and parents that holding the induction in the fall will not affect a student‚Äôs chances of getting into college.
